text:
â€œHow nice if I can join the Sangha group of Tzu Chi in Hualian, Taiwan.â€ That was my thought when my hair was shaved in 2015. Even though, my intention then was to raise $50,000 for the Compassion Support Scheme for cancer patients of all age groups. 

This year , I have just completed my 3-km daily walk from home to my office at Aljunied Crescent for 151 days during 2020 Cut Cut Cut - Cut For Compassion event. For every km I'd walked, I raised $10 for Kampung Senang. I was very reluctant to walk since becoming a mum 30 years ago, and would rely on driving even for a distance of just 2 km. A friend of donkey years challenged me by pledging a donation of $ 10 per km to Kampung Senang if I could walk to work and reduce carbon emission.

This year, besides walking a distance of 453 km , I have set the event target higher at $80,000 due to increased needs of people affected by both mental health issues and chronic illnesses. So far, we've raised only $41,000. If we can find donors for an additional $40,000, I have promised to shave my hair again. 

I sincerely hope to keep that promise.
https://www.kampungsenang.org/compassion-fund/

text:
#throwbackto #may2020 #æ¬£2020çˆ±ä½ çˆ±å¦³ #circuitbreakersg 

Pictured here with make up and in work formal attire; this was the new norm; getting dressed up at home and having interviews/meetings via zoom. This was like the don't know how many interviews i had, after sending in hundreds of job applications. End of interviews responses were almost similar; "We do not know when we can be back in office, we will still be in touch with you again.".

***

One of my resolutions for 2020 was to get back to workforce after my long hiatus of being out of the working society.

When i first made the decision to be a homemaker 7 years back, i wasn't expecting myself to be "out" for so long.

All these years, i did try to "get out" of my own current circumstances. It wasn't easy as kids' well-being and matters are always on mind; not easy to let go of a lot when I've been so hands-on with them.

In 2016, i finally stepped out and did some job searching. Was delighted that i managed to get a job offered not long after. However, we had an accidental blessing when I found out i was pregnant with #babygirl, before i signed the offer contract. Employer wasn't accepting towards my pregnancy; pretty much expected; my job offer was withdrawn.

Oh wells... Here comes another year(s) of homemaking life.

After giving birth in 2017, i decided that i should complete my degree prior to going back to workforce; at least i could have a nice portfolio as i upgraded myself during my hiatus off working society.

Another year and two passed; i finished my last paper in Dec 2018 while full-time caring for the youngest at home. Woohoo! So much effort and commitment. I finally made it.

2019 came along and i thot "yeah yeah!"; No obstruction for me to get a job. Was so looking forward.

As #bigboy advanced into his next stage of life, i thot i can settle him a little first before i start and focus more on job searching. Who knew just into the first Saturday of 2019, i had that freaky accident at home that left me handicapped for a few months. WHAT! Then physical destruction from head to toes came subsequently; caused by the effect of medications, x-rays etc etc.

image_desc: Photo shared by Cheng Wei May Lee on December 25, 2020 tagging @pix_story. May be an image of 2 people, hair, biceps, people standing and text that says 'BRING THE SHOW'.
text:
Every Friday, I go for #torturewithleonard , and if I am lucky enough to book a #bodybalance slot, #fridaywithsean (though often he manages to make it #torturewithsean with some crazy Pilates) Two completely different workouts, but I always feel so good and ready for the weekend after. Glad I was able to do both on this Christmas Day and last Friday of 2020!

This year, I totally changed my mindset towards keeping fit and have found more enjoyment and fulfilllment from my time in the gym / working out more than ever. For the first time in my life (and especially after lockdown during #circuitbreakersg), I try to give attention to various aspects of fitness- cardio, strength, core, balance, flexibility etcetc (albeit not at all equal).

Sometimes, I feel bad that I can no longer run 10km daily & 21km whenever I feel like it, but in some ways, I have gained much more!

Everyone says Iâ€™m lucky to be so â€œfitâ€ because I could run everyday (slowly)- disciplined and stubborn maybe, but definitely not fit! When I was 30, I couldnâ€™t even do five burpees, hold a plank or jump up a bench! 

Everyone starts somewhere, and fitness is just a continuous journey you do for your mind and body, and most importantly, for yourself. 

In the coming year(s), I want to add my â€œfinger fitnessâ€ back to my regime- started the Christmas morning listening to Debussy and then practicing the piano arrangement of Griegâ€™s Holberg Suite on, and it was wonderful. 

#Merry Christmas! @pix_story @sean_bmf @fitnessfirstsg #tgif

image_desc: Photo by INONE Story in Singapore. May be an image of text that says 'BEAUTY IN THE BROKEN'.
text:
â£
ğ˜’ğ˜ªğ˜¯ğ˜µğ˜´ğ˜¶ğ˜¨ğ˜ª, also known as Kintsukuroi,  is the Japanese art of restoring broken pottery with lacquered resin and powdered gold.â£
â£
The beauty of Kintsugi lies in its unapologetic display of each and every imperfection. They are displayed proudly in gold, and not hidden away. Each piece passes through masterful hands in the restoration process, and every fracture and flaw is honoured as a testament to its rich history.â£
â£
The resulting masterpieces are uniquely beautiful, and risen in value.â£
â£
Brokenness - that is one thing we all have in common. We all live with some form of brokenness - broken hearts, shattered dreams, crushed hopes, failing friendships or splintered families. â£
â£
We shy away from our flaws and imperfections, desperately keeping them away from the light of day. We keep them hidden and stored away in the lockers of our hearts. We regard them as weaknesses that could be exploited if we happen to let the walls, that we have put up to keep us safe, down.â£
â£
Perhaps the scars we all bear are the greatest sources of our strength. Perhaps our imperfections are indicators that we are not programmed robots. Perhaps our brokenness is but a reminder - that we are living and breathing despite the pain.â£
Perhaps everything beautiful, brilliant, and gorgeous about us  is not only found in what we are comfortable with showing, but also in the imperfections and scars we choose to hide.â£
â£

Do you believe in dog angels ğŸ¶ğŸ‘¼ğŸ»? Dog is god spelled backwards, and itâ€™s not hard to see why.

Harrie came home with us on 9 March 2002 and became part of our family for 6,658 days till the day he left us forever on 31 May 2020. He waited faithfully for his owner hooman to wake up on the following morning before breathing his last with a smile on his angelic face. A fluffy bichon friseÌ shaped cloud â˜ï¸ appeared in the sky shortly after his departure on 31 May. After his memorial on 1 Jun, Harrie crossed the rainbow bridge as a beautiful ğŸŒˆ formed in the sky after the rain shower ğŸŒ§, leading to an auburn sunset ğŸŒ… which also marked the end of the Circuit Breaker period. The sky turned spectacularly dramatic next early morning, followed by a couple of bichon clouds in the first few months.

- Playmate hooman, Brenda

image_desc: Photo by Ju Ann in Singapore with @ngjuann, @beyondthevines, and @converse_sg. May be an image of 1 person and outerwear.
text:
Missing the carefree days in sunny Singapore.

As I count down to meeting my kids again in #Melbourne, I also count down to re-adapting to everything new around me again. Just like when we packed our entire home into boxes and moved to Melbourne in Jan this year, I feel nervous and unsure all over again.

image_desc: Photo by Penn Pacific Denter Center-SG on December 13, 2020. May be an image of 1 person.
text:
6 common myths of gum disease

1.Â Â Â Â Â Gum disease is not that common. On the contrary, gum disease is extremely common.

Â 

2.Â Â Â Â Â Â I don't have cavities so I can't have gum disease. Cavity-free doesnâ€™t ensure you are in the clear where gum disease is concerned.

Â 

3.Â Â Â Â Â Â Having gum disease means I will lose my teeth. Not so! You donâ€™t have to lose any of your teeth to gum disease if you practice good oral hygiene.

Â 

4.Â Â Â Â Â Â Bleeding gums during pregnancy is normal. While itâ€™s true that some women develop a condition known as â€œpregnancy gingivitis,â€ itâ€™s not true that everyone experiences this.

Â 

5.Â Â Â Â Â Â Bad breath can be an indicator of gum disease. Persistent bad breath or a bad taste in your mouth can be an indicator of gum disease and other oral diseases so it is important that you uncover whatâ€™s causing the problem.

Â

text:
ğŸŒˆThere are dark days in every life, but it is very rare that we cannot find some small delight to give us hope, a glimmer of light that penetrates the cloud and reminds us of the hidden radiance. ğŸŒˆ It has been a while since I do Foodart and I wanted to paint some Christmas/winter related picture, probably because the weather is so hot and Iâ€™m missing winter Japan! Also, I wanted to find a word to sum up the year: Gratitude. (Coincidentally, it matches well with the quote of the day!) I remembered many years ago, an ex-boss first shared with me about the importance of being grateful, which I couldnâ€™t relate/understand at that time but kept the conversation in mind. After all, I was still at a very YOLO stage in life. As I get older, especially with whatâ€™s happening around us, I think now I share his sentiments well. Staying grateful is so important because it motivates us during rough moments, perseveres us through and humbles us at our best moments. While YOLO gives us the courage to pursue our dreams, having gratitude sustains us on the journey. Thatâ€™s my thoughts now. â¤ï¸â¤ï¸â¤ï¸ TGIF. ğŸŒ»

text:
During the early days of #circuitbreakersg I needed something as an activity to fill up the days of being cooped up at home. A decade ago, I was passionately pursuing music and have written and produced quite a number of songs. I stopped pursuing it after reality sets in and needs became a priority.

Long story short, I am reintroduced to the  satisfactory feeling of finishing my art. Nowadays, I don't look at it as a potential career anymore. But more of a way to show to my son, "Your dad has done this." 

Who knows... it may be something he is keen in as well!

text:
#throwbackto #april2020 #circuitbreakersg

As Coronavirus conquered the world fast and furious, Singapore went into "remote mode" in early April; in the need to break the spread. Schools stopped; businesses halted or transited to working from home; while the essential workers still headed out to serve. No one was allowed to head out, unless really necessary; this was in fact worst than confinement after giving birth. Aw man!

As per said, kiddos at home; and school learning became home-based learning; that would mean busy busy day in day out. so much monitoring to do with all of them. It's a blessing in disguise that I ain't working; i dunno how i could have coped with all the school work monitoring while still needing to WFH.

2 weeks into circuit breaker already, aside from completing work provided by her school, the vainpot was as if doing a fashion parade everyday; wearing different outfits daily; especially dresses she which she wasn't allowed to wear to school; mostly dresses by @dolliesclosetbyashley .
